WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Thank you for joining this session on The Future of Asynchronous Programming in R.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:11.000
I'm Charlie Gao, an open source engineer at Posit.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.000
I work on all things asynchronous, both in the tidyverse and in Shiny.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:24.000
I'm going to start the talk today by sharing a slide on email.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Now, email is something that every one of you is familiar with.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
And in terms of receiving email, there are two principal ways of doing so.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Either you poll for the results at intervals or you can receive push notifications.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Polling is where your client checks the server every 15 minutes.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
For example, this used to be the norm 10, 20 years ago.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:59.000
But even now, sometimes it's the only way to poll servers where there's no interface for push notifications.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:06.000
But however, if you're using a large provider, often you will get event driven push notifications.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:13.000
So as soon as email arrives on the email server, you will get notified as soon as that happens.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
This is obviously the more modern approach.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Now, if you use something like the Gmail app, then you'll often get push notifications for your Gmail account.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:36.000
But for all your other accounts, it will use the polling method and you'll get those emails with potentially a 15 minutes delay.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Now, it turns out that polling and push are two main ways to think about async in general.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:53.000
If you notice with the email example, we don't always have the email app open on our phones.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
This all happens in the background.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:05.000
So similarly, we can use this analogy when we're thinking about async in our programming.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So I'm going to use Mirai to demonstrate the two ways that we can deal with async.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Mirai is a package that I wrote that runs R code in the background very efficiently without blocking the current R session.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.000
It's rather straightforward to use.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:37.000
You simply wrap the expression you want to run with Mirai and that returns a Mirai object immediately without blocking your session.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:48.000
So once you have this object, how do you get the result of the background computation or how do you even know whether that computation has finished or not?

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:55.000
So if we take the polling approach, the way to do this would be to call unresolved on the Mirai object.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And if that's still ongoing, then it will return true, as we have here.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Now, how do we use that to use Mirai in an asynchronous fashion?

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Well, we can use a loop like this.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
So while the Mirai is unresolved, sleep for a small amount of time and then check again.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:29.000
And when you exit from that loop, you can actually access the data.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And instead of just printing the data, you would likely pass that to another function which uses the result.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:51.000
And similarly as well, instead of just sleeping for a while, you can actually do work concurrently with while this Mirai is being computed in a background process.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:58.000
So if you look at this while loop, it's very much like checking email every 15 minutes.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Except here, we're checking much more often than that because the computations we typically deal with are in the seconds or minutes.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So we want to have lower latency.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Now, before we go too far with this email analogy, I want to delve a little bit deeper about what actually happens with Mirai when tasks complete.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Because actually a Mirai is much more asynchronous.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:44.000
And what I mean is with email, when you check if there's new email, you're actually sending a request to the server and then that replies.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
If it has email, then it actually sends it back to you.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
That is not what a Mirai does.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:58.000
When you call unresolved, it is not sending anything to the background process.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Instead, what happens is when the background task completes, it will send the result straightaway back to the main process.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:15.000
And this is handled at the C level by a background thread.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
A completion callback checks the error code.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:30.000
If that's successful, it stores a pointer to the binary data that's already been received and it stores the completion status in the Mirai object itself.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.000
This is all done on the background thread in parallel to whatever's happening on the main R thread.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:51.000
This means that later when you call the R function unresolved or try to access the data element of a Mirai, all that does is check the completion status of the object.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
If that's success, then it checks if there's binary data.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:03.000
If there is, then it simply un-serializes this into an R object.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.000
We can see that this is much more efficient because we're doing as much as possible ahead of time.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:20.000
The only reason we actually have two stages is because we can't do the un-serialization and creating of an R object on the background thread.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:29.000
Because R is single-threaded, that needs to be at a time when we're actually on the main thread.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:42.000
We can see that although when we have a polling loop, it's like as if we were checking for email, but we can see that under the hood, it's not quite the same either.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
Does this help us also implement event-driven async?

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
What can we do there?

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:03.000
Well, we can, for example, use the brackets method for a Mirai object to actually wait for and collect the result.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:10.000
This is efficient in that there's no constant checking in a loop, but it also blocks the session.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:16.000
So this in itself is not a solution for event-driven async.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
For that, I will need to add to my async toolkit.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:29.000
So the packages that I will need here are promises and later.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Now, you can see that there are no hex logos for either of them.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:42.000
So that should tell you immediately that these are serious low-level packages that do the real heavy lifting here.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:51.000
So in terms of promises, that provides a high-level interface for creating these async functions.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:09.000
And what a typical signature of the key function there looks like is you wrap an object like a Mirai in as.promise, turn that into promise, and you can then access the then method.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And you pass a function to that.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:22.000
So what this means is as soon as a Mirai completes, then call this function on it.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:30.000
Later is a lower-level package, and it actually provides some of the key implementation for the async.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And the signature for the main function there is later function and seconds.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And what this does is it schedules a function to run with a certain delay.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
Now, how does Mirai promises and later work together to give you event-driven async?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
Well, let me give you an example.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:00.000
First, not of event-driven async, but of polling async.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:09.000
So what you see here is the actual as.promise method for a Mirai as it was about two years ago.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Pretty much the same.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:15.000
Simplified a little bit for clarity, but the core logic is the same.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
Let me go through this line by line.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:23.000
So this is the as.promise.Mirai method.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:29.000
We create a promise, and we pass it a function with resolve and reject.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
I won't go into that details of why.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.000
But just note, inside that function, we define another function called check.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And what this does is it calls unresolved.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:53.000
And if the Mirai is unresolved, then it will use later to schedule check again in 0.1 seconds.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:01.000
And then if it has resolved, it just takes the value, extracts the value, and it resolves or rejects the value.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And that's the definition of the check function.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
And we actually call check to kick things off.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:21.000
But essentially, you can see that this schedules itself to check every 0.1 seconds via later, whether the Mirai has resolved or not.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:30.000
So apart from polling, you can see that it's also not very efficient, because if we have something that takes quite a long time,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
then we're checking potentially hundreds, thousands of times.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And this is just one promise.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:46.000
If we have a lot of promises in whatever we're building, then we could be spending a lot of time doing these checks.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So how do we turn this into event-driven promises?

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:05.000
Well, we can see that this is, again, it's a simplified version, so it's not the entire story, but the core logic is accurate.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
You can see the stretch is maintained pretty much the same.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:15.000
But just scanning this, you can see there's no check function that repeats itself.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.000
There's no 0.1 parameter anyone in here.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:33.000
So what's changed is the core logic of your promise function is if the Mirai is unresolved, then you call this dot keep.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And dot keep is a special internal function which tells essentially the Mirai completion callback.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:48.000
So if you remember that from a few slides ago, this is something that's happening independently of the R thread,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:54.000
which processes as much of the completion as possible.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:02.000
It basically tells that callback to additionally call into later via the C interface to resolve the promise.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:09.000
So later has a C interface, which means that we're continually dealing with C code.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:19.000
We're not calling any R code, and that lets us do this completely independently of whatever's happening in R.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And what this means is that the action is scheduled as soon as the Mirai completes.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
We don't need to wait until unresolved is called or anything like that.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:34.000
And you can also see that dot keep is called once only.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:49.000
So not only do we have event driven, it is much more efficient as well because we're not potentially calling unresolved thousands of times.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:55.000
And with event driven async, we've upgraded the entire ecosystem.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So these are packages that we maintain at Posit, and we're really pleased that we've upgraded everything that we work on.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:14.000
The shiny, shiny at its core has always been event driven async, so I don't mean that.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:30.000
But we've updated our documentation for promises and for extended tasks so that users who want to run their own async code can do so via Mirai in an event driven fashion.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:43.000
We've also added async file watcher to shiny so that when you're developing an app and you change files, then that will cause the shiny app to auto reload.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:57.000
With Plumber, you've always been able to use Mirai with Plumber, but with Plumber 2, which is under development, we've implemented async at its core.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:09.000
So there's a nice at async decorator tag that you can apply to your functions to automatically turn those to use event driven async with Mirai.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
Now, if we look at the bottom row, we have Hitter 2, our HTTP client.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:24.000
We have Elmer, our LLM client, and we have ShinyChat and MCP tools packages for interacting with LLMs.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.000
They have all been upgraded to use event driven async.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:41.000
Going back to the top row, Purr has integrated with Mirai to provide it with parallel map.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:52.000
We're working on a future edition for long running operations, which we're looking to make async.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:00.000
Tidy Models as well is using Mirai to parallelize model runs.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:06.000
Again, in the future, there is potential to make some of those operations async.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:13.000
And that's all I have time for to share with you today.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:23.000
We're really glad at Posit to be working on making async more advanced and easier to use for everyone.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And I'm just really happy to share with you that we now have push notifications in R. Thank you.

